## 6. Core Data Model

The database should be designed around stable school entities.

### Main Entities

- User
- Role
- Permission
- Student
- Parent/Guardian
- Staff
- Teacher
- Class
- Section
- Subject
- Enrollment
- Academic Year
- Term
- Timetable Entry
- Attendance Record
- Exam
- Assessment
- Result
- Report Card
- Invoice
- Payment
- Expense
- Payroll Record
- Inventory Item
- Asset
- Maintenance Record
- Transport Route
- Bus
- Announcement
- Message Log
- Document
- Audit Log

### Important Relationships

- A student can have multiple guardians
- A student belongs to one class/section at a time for a given term
- A teacher can teach multiple subjects
- A timetable entry connects class, subject, teacher, room, day, and time
- Attendance belongs to a student or staff member and a date
- Results belong to student, exam, and subject
- Finance records belong to a student, payer, or school account
- Assets can have maintenance history

## 7. Permission Model

The system must protect data using RBAC.

### Suggested Roles

- Super Admin
- School Admin
- Principal
- Deputy Principal
- Teacher
- Attendance Officer
- Accountant
- HR Officer
- Librarian or Inventory Clerk
- Parent
- Student
- Transport Officer

### Permission Rules

- Super Admin can manage everything
- School Admin can manage school configuration and all modules
- Teachers can access only their classes and assigned data
- Parents can see only their own children
- Students can see only their own records
- Finance staff can access financial data only
- HR staff can access staff data only

### Security Rules

- Sensitive files must be encrypted or securely stored
- Access should always be checked at the server level
- All important actions should be logged
- Account recovery and password reset should be controlled

